<h2 id="lessons" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-6">Key Takeaways</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside">
    <li><a href="#learned1" class="text-fuchsia-800 dark:text-fuchsia-200">Market early!</a> It can be beneficial when it comes time to find playtesters.</li>
    <li><a href="#learned1" class="text-fuchsia-800 dark:text-fuchsia-200">Consistency</a> is so important when it comes to marketing because it keeps people engaged.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="plan" class="font-semibold text-xl mt-4 mb-2">Our Marketing Plan</h2>
<p> After we established our development timeline and decided that we want to do external playtesting starting in week 4, 
    we knew that we would need strong marketing from the start to gain traction and attract playtesters. 
    Knowing our target audience, we also knew that the sooner we got out our dates and times, 
    the more likely we were to get our target audience to sign-up and participate. 
</p>

<h3 id="setup" class="font-bold text-lg mt-2 mb-2">Initial Setup</h3>
<p> In Week 1, we created a Playtesting Interest email alias where we could easily track who was interested in knowing about our Playtesting sessions. 
    We also made an Instagram account 
    [<a class="text-fuchsia-600 dark:text-fuchsia-300" href="https://www.instagram.com/project.misfits/" target="_blank">@project.misfits</a>]
    and started posting information about the game there. 
    We had team members repost the information to try and reach a larger audience then what Instagram would initially push to. 
</p>
